commit_message:
Implement Mitaka ODS Documentation structure

From this etherpad:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/kolla-mitaka-documentation

Lay groundwork for structure of new documentation layout.

Further work will finish the job on this doc work.

Note in a later change I793244c47ffbe0ba304e79bacf708494e59d99c4
ansible-deployment, deploy-all-in-one-node, and quickstart.rst
will be merged into one document.

Change-Id: I42b576ffab796da6e27adc9dbf55b2ceed641c16

commit_message:
Fix docs build unknown target name error

When do the "tox docs" or "make html" in docs directory below error
is thrown in the middle of building docs and there are two broken links
in html output:

ERROR: Unknown target name: "restructuretext".
ERROR: Unknown target name: "conf override".

Change-Id: Icf4bc1b1bfbbbf2b3c2912bddd34dd5371b20afc
Closes-bug: #1510580

commit_message:
Correct the returned message when bit_length is absent

bit_length is a required field in meta. So order creation
should fail when bit_length is missing.This fix corrects
the returned message.
Before_fix:
stack@devstack:~$ curl -X POST http://localhost:9311/v1/orders/ -H
'X-Auth-Token:5c5b375d974d4391afb51c63b2ffa6dc'
-H 'content-type:application/json'
-d  '{"type":"key", "meta":{"algorithm": "AES"}}';echo
{"code": 400, "description": "Provided field value is not supported",
"title": "Bad Request"}
After_fix:
stack@devstack:~$ curl -X POST http://localhost:9311/v1/orders/ -H
'X-Auth-Token:5c5b375d974d4391afb51c63b2ffa6dc'
-H 'content-type:application/json'
-d  '{"type":"key", "meta":{"algorithm": "AES"}}';echo
{"code": 400, "description": "Provided object does not match schema
 'Order': 'bit_length' is required field for key type order.
Invalid property: 'meta'", "title": "Bad Request"}
Closes-Bug: #1482009

Change-Id: Id8c67d00d19768e7479a2e548436dc9e71f0e5cc

commit_message:
Import images publicly when package is public

When using "package-import --is-public" to import a Murano package,
make sure glance images automatically imported are also public.

Change-Id: I9460360e84cc40d7414aa5cd9f7367f5a80b8466
Partial-Bug: #1507139

commit_message:
rabbitmq: do not manage rabbitmq service anymore

rabbitmq_class was deprecated in the previous release, this patch drop it.

That means:

  * we are not installing rabbitmq service anymore.
  * rabbitmq_class parameter is deleted
  * port, cluster_disk_nodes and enabled parameters are deprecated for
    backward compatibility but port and cluster_disk_nodes have no effect
    since we don't install rabbitmq anymore.
  * unit tests are updated

Note: this patch changes only spec tests for rabbitmq.pp

Co-Authored-By: Emilien Macchi <emilien@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I373043294a4f3258799e613176725030fcbd2a50
(cherry picked from commit d41437e0193fa4ac0f2f4ac7ce341b76a4314c6e)

commit_message:
Spec file for the Cloudify plugin

It is based on the support-tosca-format spec.
I have modified it in the areas where the two formats differ -
my assignee information,
data related to the packaging and testing of deployments,
proposed changes, etc.

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add ironic logs collector

This change introduces new UDP listener for rsyslog

Rsyslog listener on ironic node is need to collect logs from baremetal nodes.
All received logs should be saved in /var/log/remote/ directory.

Partially Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic
Change-Id: I7385fbc13067cf0bb42beb6b86304e6671ea2f1d

commit_message:
Don't update metadata_proxy if metadata is not enabled

When enable_metadata_proxy is false, the agent instance will
not have metadata_driver. And agent should avoid using it.

Change-Id: Ia18dc5dea23de49b97c8f225532531eb9232fb51
Closes-Bug: #1510399
(cherry picked from commit ce3a31faff35e6f177bd747cf8427a9f00d05af0)

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add haproxy services for Ironic

This change adds new haproxy services needed by ironic:
* ironic-api - on management and public VIPs
* ironic-api - on baremetal VIP
* swift-baremetal - proxy for swift servers on baremetal VIP
* noop tests

Partially Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic

Change-Id: I5ced9e5706fcba9fc60a07771ae51538945895a9

commit_message:
Remove service management from nova-manage

The service command of nova-manage tool provides duplicated functionality
with the nova REST API so this spec proposes to first deprecate then
remove the service command.

Implements: blueprint remove-service-management-from-nova-manage
Change-Id: I5baaf42c0d9f0aaf56ee611d96478289e1357c6a

commit_message:
swift-ring-builder can't remove a device with zero weight

If a device with 0 weight is tried to remove, the following rebalance
does not write changes into builder file.

Scenario:
$ swift-ring-builder object.builder set_weight --id 1 0.00
$ swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance
Wait for moving files out of the device id=1.
$ swift-ring-builder object.builder remove --id 1
$ swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance
In fact, the device id=1 is not removed after rebalance (must be --force used).

Change-Id: Iad5a444023eae9882a3addd7f119ff4d18559ddd

commit_message:
Always send status update for processed floating ips

Currently l3 agent skips status update for floating ips in case
status didn't change: this might be wrong if status has changed
on server side while agent was processing. See bug for details.

L3 agent skips floating ip processing in case ip address exists
on external device. So we can still skip status update for such
floating ips.

Closes-Bug: #1505557

Conflicts:

	neutron/tests/unit/agent/l3/test_agent.py

Change-Id: I908fe5a0555f68ab85e7d199c36a903b915e103f
(cherry picked from commit 7592b17b8793c0e296c77bd17929f3db37f1483e)

commit_message:
Remove excessive fallback iptables ACCEPT rules

The previous code was generating a fallback ACCEPT rule for every
port when there should only be one at the very end. The reason that
this wasn't causing a bug is because we have a duplicate rule remover
that was silently throwing away the extras and it happened to get them
in the right order.

Closes-Bug: #1502906
Change-Id: I83cf574f93b512be1ccefdc8da63e1783d279233
(cherry picked from commit ea8de8a9dd808b1379060e0ce578b8129f45c3ae)

commit_message:
Remove root owned ipsec.secrets for ensure_configs

Since LibreSwan requires that ipsec.secrets be owned by root, the
strategy of rewriting the ipsec.secrets file by writing to a temp file
and renaming causes a permission error and fails to overwrite. This
patch removes the target ipsec.secrets file before running the
ensure_configs operations.

This patch also changes the logging in the _process_running check from
error to info. It isn't an error and will occur under normal operations.

Conflicts:
	neutron_vpnaas/tests/unit/services/vpn/device_drivers/test_ipsec.py

Change-Id: Id00613e7ca11310e4f65b557b136e02d9783d0d4
(cherry picked from commit 5047aa295164ff64963ab365cd63138273aaa3e4)

commit_message:
Add retry to unless part of nova flavor m1.micro

The openstack-controller task fails if nova-flavor list returns
a 503 error code, causing the nova flavor-create command to
be run unnecessarily.

Nova flavor-create fails if it already exists, but sometimes
nova flavor-list fails because nova or keystone API is not
ready. The unless statement should retry the same number
of tries until nova flavor-list is able to return a result.

Change-Id: I106dae88fd397c5b3ef137597ad8a4d70e50d134
Closes-Bug: #1511695

commit_message:
Use assertTrue/False instead of assertEqual(T/F)

The usage of assertEqual(True/False, ***) should be changed
to a meaningful format of assertTrue/False(***).

Change-Id: I4e1918426e39a70c8b971d171d774ad5e241f2ae
Closes-Bug: #1512207

commit_message:
avoid using isolation level

depending on sql driver, REPEATABLE READ isolation level may lock
an entire table and cause write timeouts. isolation level was set
originally to ensure consistent reads between 2 queries required to
build events. that said, we can avoid table locks by making
assumption that the 1st query is the correct base and any difference
given by 2nd query can be discarded.

Change-Id: Ic53e1addf38a4d5934b4e627c4c974c6db42517e
Closes-Bug: #1506717
(cherry picked from commit 898cd3d036c4358aa16f7b3e2028365dc9829213)

commit_message:
Split node configuration and customization docs

There are two distinct interfaces currently described in the
extra_config docs:

1. ExtraConfig *parameters*, which influence the configuration of
services which are already integrated via the default templates

2. ExtraConfig *resources* which are designed to enable node
customization and third-party integration.

So, for the avoidance of confusion, don't conflate these interfaces
in the docs and split them into two pages.

Also, the "customization" part is due for update with several new
interfaces, so the paramters section could easily get missed
at the end of all the resources orientated description.

Change-Id: I64d67f6526c505185dfe663b087b0f0576b09750

commit_message:
Use assertFalse and assertTrue instead of assertEqual

Since `assertFalse` and `assertTrue` are provided for asserting
boolean expression, seems it is not official to use assertEqual.

Change-Id: Id522f1c72cbd1cc079c860f611dcb922b7d89525

commit_message:
Update create_volume to use versionedobjects

The following patch updates create_volume API to use
volume versionedobjects.  It only includes changes to
the core cinder code.  Changes in the drivers are
left to each driver maintainer to update.

Note that this patch DOES NOT try to use
object dot notation everywhere, since it would
increase the size of the patch.  Instead, it
will be done in subsequent patches.

Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>
Change-Id: Ic1b0f09132f8fc500b29650abbd57f18ea8bd9dd
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

commit_message:
Adding nodes not in an env to group is bad request

When you tried to add node that is not added to cluster you got 500
error. Now this situation is handled and 400 is returned along with an
explanation

Change-Id: I8fd20c7a862caccd9c778672d4527343386a5d5a
Closes-bug: #1508398

commit_message:
Rework translation-cleanup

Rework for switch to Zanata:
* Update for Zanata.
* Do not import anymore new translations, with Zanata those will be
  imported automatically.

commit_message:
fix lp project name to repo name conversion

The ironic-python-agent repo and launchpad name are the same, but the
conversion script tries to strip the python- part out of the middle.
Change the pattern so it only removes python- if it is a prefix in the
name.

Change-Id: I5c2f4c4c86e0f2e5528efd28f2c46e10ca7f74f6

commit_message:
Fix update_modules.sh to handle missing timeout cmd

This change fixes the update_modules.sh scrip so that if the 'timeout'
command is not available it will no longer error.  Previously if the
system did not have a 'timeout' command, the update_modules.sh script
would fail silently and return 1.

Change-Id: I7b469b65a30bfe2af8acf62bebabf10c9af1e374
Closes-Bug: #1510665

thanks for all the comments - I believe I've addressed all of them. 

SETTING -1 FOR NOW because this code is apparently hazardous to the health of ovs:

I moved the cleanup outof the addCleanup, because it was causing a segfault - basically, tearDown() is apparently [1] called before the cleanup methods. This meant that the int-br (and tap-xXXX where dnsmasq is attached) was being pulled out from under dnsmasq. Aparrently this is very bad for the health of the kernel.

With ovs 2.3.0 [2] in it's present form, this code with succeed on the first run,and then segfault ovs on the next run, reliably. After this only a reboot will bring ovs back (modprobe, restarting ovs, nothing). I need to investigate some more, but any ideas would be very very helpful,

thanks!

(6 comments)

Hi Cedric. Thanks for very much for taking the time to look at this. If by 'real ports' you mean 'ports attached to bona-fide vm' :) then thanks very much for raising this point. I believe Rossella raises a similar concern on the l2-agent tests at [1]. When I started working on this stuff I assumed that these tests would be 'functional testing of the agent in isolation', especially because we have integration testing with tempest. I also recently stumbled on John's spec at [2] for full stack neutron (only) integration testing - his definition there of what our in-tree functional testing is like imo matches my approach.

Please let me know what you think and I'd be very interested to hear from others too. I have replied inline to your points, I won't put out a revision until I get some clarity on some of those points please.

Final point - time.now() and in-tree, our functional testing for the dhcp agent is at exactly 0% coverage; I think there is some value in the testing being done here and it can always act as a base on which to build. The review is already at ~250 lines, as a first commit towards in-tree functional testing for the dhcp agent I don't think it is horrible, but of course I am a bit biased ;) (the question here is, wasn't sure if the -1 was for the inline nits, or for the point you raise and which I discussed above, if my assumption is correct)

thanks again for your thoughts,

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/140042/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/128257/18/specs/kilo/full-stack-white-box-tests.rst"}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2014-12-31 14:33:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(3 comments)

The -1 is because - imo - assert_allocations could be done through a unit test and we should ensure dnsmasq provides the expected service.

dnsmasq testing could be done by creating a namespace with a port (defined in host_opts file), run dhclient $interface and check $interface "ifconfig".'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-12-31 18:12:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)

Good work Marios!'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-01-02 11:56:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)

I believe we should avoid parts which don't tests real system interaction (dnsmasq in this case) and which should belong to unit testing (in my opinion). 

Real DHCP requests (probably forged or via dhcpclient on a netns with explicit mac) would be necessary IMHO.

BTW, good work, this is something we need to stop testing such basic behavior on tempest."}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2015-01-05 07:44:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

I agree with what the others said: you could use [1] to fake a VM port and make sure it receives DHCP services, but you're much better off testing it on a lower level (unit tests using mocking) until that patch (and my full-stack) merges.

So - as per discussion I see two things needed - actual dhcp requests to the dnsmasq process started by neutron (using the mac addresses in the host file) to verify and verification that dnsmasq was actually started. I am having an issue with the spawned dnsmasq process so grateful for any comments if you've come across this.

Basically dnsmasq is spawned by the tests as user 'nobody' and the host/opts/addn_hosts files are created under /tmp... this results in a permissions problem with the trace like [1] ; meaning that we configure dnsmasq with static lease but it cannot read the host file for the allocations it is meant to serve. I've tried changing the user in /etc/dnsmasq.conf, selinux setenforce 0, and also installed latest dnsmasq from source (2.72). Anyone seen this before? I think might be specific to the way tests are being run,

thanks! marios

Assaf, the main reason why we use current solution with creating directory at /etc/netns and etc. is that dhclient on ubuntu not properly works with custom config that passes with -cf flag (version isc-dhclient-4.2.4) it looks like dhclient just ignore config and use system config instead (at /etc/dhcp/dhclient.conf). Changing the system dhclient.conf is not good idea
BTW, I found the way to resolve a problem with modifying machine's hostname.
dhclient-script (/usr/sbin/dhclient-script in Fedora) is invoked by dhclient. In dhclient-script we can see:

    if [ -n "${new_host_name}" ] && need_hostname; then
      hostname ${new_host_name} || echo "See -nc option in dhclient(8) man page."
    fi

that means, modifying hostname is depended on need_hostname function (need_hostname is defined in /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/network-functions in Fedora) and need_hostname return 0 if current hostname is equal to one of them: (none), localhost, localhost.localdomain. So, if your machine with fedora has localhost.localdomain hostname (like my), dhclient will override it. commit_message:
Adds base in-tree functional testing of the dhcp agent (OVS)

Adds some utility methods and a couple of base test cases that
can be added to. These first tests exercise the ovs driver (dnsmasq)
and so the code is organised accordingly - OVS specific test cases
are defined in a DHCPAgentOVSTestFramework

Partial-Bug: #1469065
Co-Authored-By: Cedric Brandily <zzelle@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sergey Belous <sbelous@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Ic9d5a2f2b8014e4d81f5e5f6fa58b119a86de075

[{'created': '2015-10-30 02:27:46.000000000', 'message': 'Address issues with Trove eventlet monkey-patching

There have been several issues with the way in which Trove does its
monkey patching including the fact that oslo.messaging gets rather
annoyed if eventlet is incorrectly patched.

So, this change follows the recommendations in (note multi-line URL)

http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/\
openstack-specs/specs/eventlet-best-practices.html

Other things to keep in mind are that the old way in which Trove was
doing monkey patching was flawed. What Trove did was to first call

eventlet.monkey_patch(all=True, thread=False)

with the fond hope that this meant monkey patching of "all but thread"
would be done. However, the documentation and the code for the
function are pretty clear that this is not the case.

See: http://eventlet.net/doc/basic_usage.html

"If all is True, then all modules are patched regardless of the other
arguments. If its False, then the rest of the keyword arguments
control patching of specific subsections of the standard library."

This also explains why debugger didn't quite work well with Trove, the
whole purpose of the shenanigans that Trove was attempting to do.

Then there's also the wonderful fact that you can't reliably check
(with is_monkey_patched()) whether the 'thread' module is in fact
monkey patched. See (note the multi-line URL)

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/32452110/\
does-eventlet-do-monkey-patch-for-threading-module

Therefore the code actually attempts to issue a meaningful warning if
debugging is attempted with eventlet monkey patched.

This is related to a number of other bugs I've found that indict the
way in which projects have monkey_patched eventlet. See, for example,
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156942/,
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153699/, and
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1417386.

Change-Id: I92ab95f9113eae862e0cd56e7d65cdd48944615f
Closes-Bug: 1365736
Closes-Bug: 1510542
'}]
commit_message:
Address issues with Trove eventlet monkey-patching

There have been several issues with the way in which Trove does its
monkey patching including the fact that oslo.messaging gets rather
annoyed if eventlet is incorrectly patched.

So, this change follows the recommendations in (note multi-line URL)

http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/\
openstack-specs/specs/eventlet-best-practices.html

Other things to keep in mind are that the old way in which Trove was
doing monkey patching was flawed. What Trove did was to first call

eventlet.monkey_patch(all=True, thread=False)

with the fond hope that this meant monkey patching of "all but thread"
would be done. However, the documentation and the code for the
function are pretty clear that this is not the case.

See: http://eventlet.net/doc/basic_usage.html

"If all is True, then all modules are patched regardless of the other
arguments. If its False, then the rest of the keyword arguments
control patching of specific subsections of the standard library."

This also explains why debugger didn't quite work well with Trove, the
whole purpose of the shenanigans that Trove was attempting to do.

Then there's also the wonderful fact that you can't reliably check
(with is_monkey_patched()) whether the 'thread' module is in fact
monkey patched. See (note the multi-line URL)

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/32452110/\
does-eventlet-do-monkey-patch-for-threading-module

Therefore the code actually attempts to issue a meaningful warning if
debugging is attempted with eventlet monkey patched.

This is related to a number of other bugs I've found that indict the
way in which projects have monkey_patched eventlet. See, for example,
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156942/,
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153699/, and
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1417386.

Change-Id: I92ab95f9113eae862e0cd56e7d65cdd48944615f
Closes-Bug: 1365736
Closes-Bug: 1510542

commit_message:
Refactor the datastore manager classes

There is a large amount of boiler-plate code in each datastore manager.
As more managers are added, the time involved in maintaining all this
code wil continue to grow. To alleviate this, a base manager class
has been added where all common code can reside.

The initial refactoring just moved some of the obvious code (such as
rpc_ping and update_status) into the base class, along with defining
properties that can be used to further abstract functionality
going forward.

The issue of having instances move in-and-out of ACTIVE state has
also been fixed by adding a flag file that is written by the base
class once prepare has finished successfully.

Closes-Bug: #1482795
Closes-Bug: #1487233
Partially Implements: blueprint datastore-manager-refactor
Change-Id: I603cf2ddebab1d7a5c874cd66431f803aaee2d42

commit_message:
Incorrect usage of python-novaclient

This usage was causing an annoying error message. I've addressed it in
a configurable way. There's a new config parameter that can be
changed.

Change-Id: I78832d0bb2ecdc49901b74d3811764a9676f7c8b
Closes-Bug: #1493576

commit_message:
Just use /etc/openstack/clouds.yaml

devstack writes out clouds.yaml now to /etc - so we don't need to much
around with this anymore.

Change-Id: I2badb80a1f031382010288eb7e0cf1c960a1570a

commit_message:
Revert "Append EXTRA_ADMIN_NETWORKS to dnsmasq.template"

This reverts commit 5787af40904d6e209777f936550f06b6930ffb57.
And also removes parameter 'extra_admin_nets' from unit tests.

We're implementing automatic configuration of DHCP ranges in
dnsmasq so this workaround is no longer needed.

Co-Authored-By: Aleksandr Didenko <adidenko@mirantis.com>

DocImpact: we should remove documentation about manual update
of dnsmasq.template file here:
https://docs.mirantis.com/openstack/fuel/fuel-7.0/operations.html#configuring-multiple-cluster-networks

Change-Id: Idd4d6051d5b4aeba504920126e697135c683a78b
Blueprint: dynamic-dnsmasq

commit_message:
Support NFS backend for Glance (via Pacemaker)

Adds support for NFS backend in Glance by allowing the storage directory
for the 'file' backend to be a mount managed by Pacemaker. Default
behavior is unchanged.

Since the Pacemaker-related parameters are not exposed on top level,
change storage-environment.yaml to use parameter_defaults instead of
parameters.

Depends on a Heat fix for environment file's parameter_defaults to
work well with JSONs and comma delimited lists (see Depends-On).

Change-Id: I6e7e2eaf6919b955650c0b32e1629a4067602c89
Depends-On: I85b13a79dbc97a77e20c0d5df8eaf05b3000815e

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add firewall rules for baremetal network

This change introduces new iptables chain for baremetal network

Following rules added:
* new chain for baremetal network
* allow pings from VIP on controller
* allow rsyslog on conductor
* allow TFTP on conductor
* drop all other traffic from baremetal network

Additional helper module for TFTP added.

Partially Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic
Change-Id: Idb756c48c88da0dbdd0a8850df4f268ceed42cf2

commit_message:
Support Berkshelf for Chef applications

The goal of this specification is to make possible the use of Berkshelf
(http://berkshelf.com/) to manage Chef cookbooks dependencies when Chef
is used to configure a VM.

Partially Implements: blueprint support-chef-berkshelf
Change-Id: Id1dbb2208fc02e37a9c89dff6dda8855a59c851d

We would like to have decomposition for stable/liberty as well as to have an ovsvapp_mech_driver compatibility with master and stable/liberty branch of Neutron.

At the same time, we would like to cut off the stable/liberty branch of networking-vsphere repo compatible with stable/liberty neutron, currently it is dependent on neutron master which have decomposed code.

If we cut-off the stable/liberty branch with current code of networking-vsphere, it won't work with stable/liberty codebase of Neutron which doesnt have the decomposed code and broke the solution.

Hence, we would like to backport this to stable/liberty if window is open and tag the networking-vsphere repo."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-02 10:38:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

No. We don't remove features in stable branches."}, {'account_id': 10370, 'date': '2015-11-02 11:23:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Ihar, Cedric: How about this https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240825/ to solve our problem. In which case, we don't want this https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240765/ needs to be backported."}, {'account_id': 10370, 'date': '2015-11-02 11:25:19.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Let's have a discussion on this,
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240825/."}]

Looks good. I think this refactor is greatly needed and already overdue. I just wanted to pinpoint a couple of points.'}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-10-08 20:10:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

[Note for the next stage of refactoring]
One more thing we should consider before more datastores start supporting user and database functions.

Every datastore currently receives/returns the objects from/to the wire in a 'serialized' form (this is the API level). It de-serializes/serializes them into/from objects (guestagent models) with which it works internally (that's also where the value checking is performed).
This object 'dualism' possibly ties the derived guest-agent implementation to the API details and also leads to confusion about what kind of object is coming in/going out to/from the gues-agent methods.

As noted in my previous comment, most of the logging and exception handling should ultimately move to the base class. This will require the base class call 'protected' (implementation) methods overriden in the derived classes.

It would be great if we could use the base class to 'shield' derived guest-agents from these serialized forms (implementation details) altogether. The base (API) method would receive serialized form and it would pass it to the derived class implementation method as an appropriate object (applying the right model to deserialize it). Similarly for calls that return objects."}, {'account_id': 10440, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:08:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Refactor the datastore manager classes

There is a large amount of boiler-plate code in each datastore manager.
As more managers are added, the time involved in maintaining all this
code will continue to grow. To alleviate this, a base manager class
needs to be created where all common code can reside.

This spec outlines the proposal for accomplishing the refactor.

Change-Id: Id2a0c78754e9e0cac4502632f02792b01c3745d4
References: blueprint datastore-manager-refactor

Remove unneeded puppet module

Because puppet::pull is still used by tools task, it has been renamed
osnailyfacter::puppet_pull.

Closes-bug: 1507532

commit_message:
Adjust rmq stats collector settings

The stats collector falls behind under
high load on the messaging system.
The suggested optimization is to increase
the stats polling and disable rates
processing in management UI:
rabbit.collect_statistics_interval=30000
rabbitmq_management.rates_mode=none.
The new hiera parameter rabbit_config_management_variables
may be used to override the rates_mode to other values.

Related upstream PR
https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-rabbitmq/pull/407

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1510835

Change-Id: I9a3179a4f002064c9b6d2621a49bb0aa9aa707c7
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Trivial clean up: do not use plural form in command arguments.

It is a general rule that we don't use plural form for the name of
command arguments. But class DeleteServer() is still using "servers".
So use "server instead".

[{'created': '2015-10-27 16:47:21.000000000', 'message': "[Reports] Change template lookup_dirs for ui.utils.get_template()

rally.ui.utils.get_template() has package distribution directory
in its lookup_dirs - this allowed searching templates in whole
rally project tree.

This is useful in some cases when we just have unpacked rally,
sources for example if we render templates from tests/ci/
on gates. However this lookup directory looks strange after
we install rally, because it becomes pointing to python
packages directory.

This patch changes this lookup directory to system root `/',
therefore rally can get arbitrary template by its absolute
path. This is logical abd gives extra flexibility.

commit_message:
[Reports] Change template lookup_dirs for ui.utils.get_template()

ui.utils.get_template() has strange directory in its lookup_dirs:

 os.path.abspath(os.path.join(templates_dir, "..", "..", "..")

This dirctory points on Rally package parent directory and is
used only by gates (to get templates from tests/ci/).

This patch:
  * replaces this strange directory with system root "/",
    so gates can get template by its absolute path
  * makes proper changes in tests/ci scripts

Change-Id: I31cc925a2c592af17bd7411d1c989d1b4ced8b6f

commit_message:
Remove deployment graph config for patching

Delete deployment graph configuration for patching. Delete condition that
yields this configuration when cluster asked for deployment graph.

Nailgun tests were failing due to incorrect tests. Previously, they rely
on that default admin (shared) network is created and exists in
database, and when it's not exist (cluster wasn't created by some
previous test, or was removed) - they fail. Moreover, the unexpected
mock object were passed to validator as cluster argument that may
cause further possible failures.

So let's Create a cluster instance and pass it to network configuration
validator, and ensure it works against actual data.

Change-Id: I0c2b5e99d279acfbdca62cd3ceed86ea36b58923
Closes-Bug: #1511725
"}]
commit_message:
Fix network configuration validator tests

Nailgun tests were failing due to incorrect tests. Previously, they rely
on that default admin (shared) network is created and exists in
database, and when it's not exist (cluster wasn't created by some
previous test, or was removed) - they fail. Moreover, the unexpected
mock object were passed to validator as cluster argument that may
cause further possible failures.

So let's Create a cluster instance and pass it to network configuration
validator, and ensure it works against actual data.

Change-Id: I0c2b5e99d279acfbdca62cd3ceed86ea36b58923
Closes-Bug: #1511725

commit_message:
Python 3: Use six.moves.range

The function `xrange` was renamed to `range` in Python 3.

* Remove `xrange` occurences so that Python 3 tests can pass. Use
  `six.moves.range` instead to get the right function in both cases.
* Add a hacking check to prevent future usage of `xrange`.

Change-Id: I9c33e978238b8b661bff98270c1af5ec629b0d69
Closes-Bug: #1261984

commit_message:
DHCP agent: log when reloading allocations for a new VM port

This will help us to see more clearly if failing DHCP for a new VM -
as seen in failures such as the following traceback from [1] - is
caused by DHCP configuration being too slow, as suggested by the
referenced bug.

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/home/aqua/tempest/tempest/test.py", line 125, in wrapper
    return f(self, *func_args, **func_kwargs)
  File "/home/aqua/tempest/tempest/scenario/test_server_basic_ops_38.py", line 105, in test_server_basicops
    self.verify_ssh()
  File "/home/aqua/tempest/tempest/scenario/test_server_basic_ops_38.py", line 95, in verify_ssh
    private_key=self.keypair['private_key'])
  File "/home/aqua/tempest/tempest/scenario/manager.py", line 310, in get_remote_client
    linux_client.validate_authentication()
  File "/home/aqua/tempest/tempest/common/utils/linux/remote_client.py", line 55, in validate_authentication
    self.ssh_client.test_connection_auth()
  File "/home/aqua/tempest/tempest/common/ssh.py", line 150, in test_connection_auth
    connection = self._get_ssh_connection()
  File "/home/aqua/tempest/tempest/common/ssh.py", line 87, in _get_ssh_connection
    password=self.password)
tempest.exceptions.SSHTimeout: Connection to the 172.17.205.21 via SSH timed out.
User: cirros, Password: None

[1] http://logs.openstack.org/39/194939/19/check/gate-grenade-dsvm-neutron/82a7e58/

Change-Id: I5d77762bf8d4caa2e6f8b3527a30bf80bac62085
Related-Bug: #1453350

This change introduces configuration of new flat network in Neutron.
In case if network settings contains information about 'physnet-ironic'
physnet then Ironic is enabled and 'baremetal' flat network should be
configured in neutron settings.

Also for Ironic should be created 'baremetal' network and subnet in neutron.
This network will used for provision baremetal servers.

User should be able to set cidr and allocation pools for baremetal network.
This change add consideration of parameter 'allocation_pool' in L3 network
data when create new network in Neutron.

Change-Id: Icdb557063bbaf5bb0b5b6ac6c8233e3c3b17e94c
Implemets: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic (partially)

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add baremetal network for Ironic

This change introduces configuration of new flat network in Neutron.
In case if network settings contains information about 'physnet-ironic'
physnet then Ironic is enabled and 'baremetal' flat network should be
configured in neutron settings.

Partially Implemets: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic

Change-Id: Icdb557063bbaf5bb0b5b6ac6c8233e3c3b17e94c

commit_message:
Better tolerate deleted OVS ports in OVS agent

This change will not force a resync in the case where a virtual machine is
deleted, and therefore its OVS port deleted, in between the time an RPC
call was made to get the devices and where we make the call to correlate
those devices to vif ports.

Change-Id: Ie55eb69ad7ee177f0cf8ee8fc7fc585fbd0d4a22
Closes-Bug: #1499488
(cherry picked from commit 0a300a2277a583fe28b00db2571982928c752554)

commit_message:
Set geography for O to Catalonia

Barcelona is the largest city in Catalonia which is one of three
"Nationalities" in Spain.
